  "text": "HIT IgG antibodies bind to FcγRIIA, a low-affinity receptor present at low copy numbers in platelets (1000 to 2000 receptors per cell). However, PF4/H/IgG immune complexes may strongly activate platelets by cross-linking FcγRIIA receptors, and this process is a key event in pathogenesis of HIT [CITATION_1] . In our study, HIPA tests performed with HIT For personal use only. on September 14, 2017. by guest www.bloodjournal.org From plasma showed that platelets isolated from healthy donors carrying the CD148 276P/326Q alleles were hyporesponsive to anti-PF4/H antibodies. In addition, subjects expressing the CD148 276P/326Q isoform exhibited a lower response to murine monoclonal antibodies ALB6 and PL2-49, which also activate platelets via FcγRIIA receptors [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Moreover, these subjects were also hyporesponsive to low concentrations of collagen (1 and 0.5 µg/mL) while platelet responses to high doses of collagen and thrombin were similar to those of nonmutated individuals. These results are consistent with those previously obtained with murine CD148-deficient platelets that failed to aggregate when activated by low doses of collagen but that responded normally to higher doses 15,30 . Moreover, our experiments showed that the lag time measured after activation of platelets by HIT antibodies or monoclonal antibodies cross linking with FcγRIIA was more influenced by CD148 SNPs than the maximum aggregation.",
